*******************Transaction***************************

Transaction is a sequence of operations performed as a single logical unit of work. 
A transaction must be atomic, consistent, isolated, and durable (ACID properties).

transaction is a unit of work that is performed against a database. 
It is a way to ensure that a series of operations are executed in a way that maintains the integrity of the database.

Transactions are used to ensure that a series of operations are executed in a way that maintains the integrity of the database.

@transactional is an annotation that can be applied to a method or a class to indicate that the method or class should be executed within a transaction. 
When a method or class is annotated with @transactional, the framework will automatically start a transaction before the method is executed and commit the transaction after the method is executed.

If an exception is thrown during the execution of the method, the transaction will be rolled back to ensure that the database remains in a consistent state.

It creates a proxy around the annotated method or class, which manages the transaction lifecycle.

If the class is implementing an interface, the proxy will be created using JDK dynamic proxies.
If the class is not implementing an interface, the proxy will be created using CGLIB (Code Generation Library).

Diff between JDK dynamic proxies and CGLIB proxies:
1. JDK dynamic proxies can only proxy interfaces, while CGLIB can proxy classes.
2. JDK dynamic proxies use reflection to invoke methods, 
	while CGLIB generates bytecode to create a subclass of the target class and overrides the methods.
3. JDK dynamic proxies are generally faster than CGLIB proxies because they use reflection,
    while CGLIB proxies can be slower due to the overhead of generating bytecode and creating subclasses.

